SUMMARIZER="E">

A study published today in the New England Journal of Medicine indicates that an 
intestinal operation to lower cholesterol of heart attack patients reduced the risk of a 
second heart attack. Called a partial ileal bypass, changes the route of the small intestine 
so that one-third of it is bypassed. Although lowering the risk of a second heart attack, a 
major drawback of the procedure is chronic diarrhea, which can last for years. Patients 
also are more prone to kidney stones, gallstones, and intestinal obstructions. Patients with 
severe heart damage were not helped by the procedure.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d075"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="AP880829-0222"
SELECTOR="B"
SUMMARIZER="E">

Aspirin can be a significant factor in reducing the number of heart attacks. Taking a 
single aspirin every other day could cut the risk of a heart attack in half. When used with 
a clot-dissolving drug, given within 24 hours of a heart attack, the chance of a second 
heart attack is reduced from 13 percent to 8 percent.  Many doctors still are not using 
clot-dissolving drugs but it is felt that, in the future, their use will be considered safe 
enough to allow paramedics to administer them to patients on the way to the hospital. 
Using a clot dissolver and aspirin could save 25,000 lives a year.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d075"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="AP900322-0112"
SELECTOR="B"
SUMMARIZER="E">

Danish studies of the drug Verapamil, a calcium channel blocker, show that the drug 
reduces the chance of a new heart attack in patients recovering from a heart attack. This 
is the first trial to indicate that calcium blockers may be helpful after a heart attack. 
Verapamil is about  as effective as beta blockers in protecting people after heart attacks 
and may be useful in instances where beta blockers cannot be used. Many people do not 
tolerate beate blockers, especially those suffering from asthma and emphysema. 
Verapamil was effective in decreasing mortality in the first 12 to 18 months following a 
heart attack.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d075"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="WSJ910418-0105"
SELECTOR="B"
SUMMARIZER="E">

An experiment indicates that a blood and urine test of individuals with high blood 
pressure can pinpoint those patients most likely to have a heart attack. The test also can 
determine those patients whose risk of heart attack is extremely low. The test determines 
whether the kidneys are releasing too much renin into the blood. People with high levels 
of rennin are at a high risk of heart attack. The test can be especially useful for 
determining heart attack risks in patients without any of the usual risk factors. Those in 
this group with high rennin levels were seven times more likely to suffer a heart attack.</SUM>

<SUM
