TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="AP890115-0014"
SELECTOR="B"
SUMMARIZER="E">

Although the death rate from heart attacks and blood vessels diseases has dropped 24 
percent in the last decade, they remain the number one cause of death in the United 
States. This decline can be attributed to changing life styles, which includes fewer 
cigarettes, better food and better medical treatment.  Despite this decrease, it is believed 
that up to 50 percent of the heart disease cased by the clogging of blood vessels feeding 
the heart; the most lethal heart ailment. Lowering cholesterol levels and educating people 
to get to the hospital  within three to four hours of the first sign of a heart attack would 
significantly increase survival rates.</SUM> 

<SUM
DOCSET="d075"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="AP880428-0041"
SELECTOR="B"
SUMMARIZER="E">

Releasing a heart attack victim from the hospital as soon as three days after their attack 
are becoming more common with new medical treatments. The early discharges are made 
possible with the introduction of tissue plasminogen activator, or TPA, and balloon 
angioplasty. TPA, given right after a heart attack, can dissolve clots while angioplasty 
can open up clogged arteries. Patients sent home early can return to work earlier that 
those kept longer, while the number of medical problems suffered by both groups after 
six months were similar. The earlier release also has the benefit of significantly reducing 
medical costs.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d075"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="AP881115-0113"
SELECTOR="B"
SUMMARIZER="E">

Phase  2 of the Thrombolysis in Miocardial Infarction Trial, or TIMI-II, has shown that 
the routine practice of using balloon angioplasty is unnecessary and should be 
abandoned. The first phase of the study showed that giving tissue plasminogen activator, 
or TPA,  a clot-dissolving drug, right after a heart attack dramatically improved chances 
of survival. A trial involving a group given angiolplasty and a group given TPA did not 
show any difference in survival rates after a year. This finding indicates that smaller 
community hospitals can treat most heart attack patients. Patients needing angioplasty 
could be transferred to larger hospitals for treatment.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d075"
TYPE="PERDOC"
